hampagne-Ardenne, France","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde D'Avesnes was born in 1065, in Avesnes, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, her father, Wallérand D'AVESNES-DE GAND, was 31 and her mother, Blanche de Beaufort, was 14. She married Nicolas de Rumigny in 1084. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 12 November 1138, in Rumigny, Ardennes, Champagne-Ardenne, France, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1065–12 novembre 1138":"1065–12. november 1138","1065–1138":"1065–1138","1055–1096":"1055–1096","1094–1153":"1094–1153","1034–1094":"1034–1094","1051–1107":"1051–1107","1107":"1107","1138":"1138","1034":"1034","1055":"1055","1065":"1065","12 novembre 1138":"12. november 1138","1153":"1153","1096":"1096","1084":"1084","1051":"1051","1094":"1094","Avesnes-le-Comte, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Avesnes-le-Comte, Pas-de-Calais, Haut